<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">The 10 underlying dimensions</span><h2 class="h2">How the score is computed</h2><p class="body">Each company is scored 0-10 on each of 10 dimensions. Total: 0-100.</p><div class="table-wrap"><table class="t"><thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Dimension</th><th>What 10/10 looks like</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td><strong>Leadership commitment</strong></td><td>CEO uses AI daily; AI is a documented exec priority</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td><strong>Named ownership</strong></td><td>One human accountable with 10+ hrs/week protected</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td><strong>Platform consolidation</strong></td><td>One LLM platform deeply adopted across functions</td></tr><tr><td>4</td><td><strong>Production workflows</strong></td><td>5+ workflows in daily production use across functions</td></tr><tr><td>5</td><td><strong>Documentation discipline</strong></td><td>Each workflow has a one-page doc; prompt library maintained</td></tr><tr><td>6</td><td><strong>Measurement</strong></td><td>Baseline + post-rollout metrics tracked quarterly</td></tr><tr><td>7</td><td><strong>Team adoption breadth</strong></td><td>80%+ of affected team uses AI tools weekly</td></tr><tr><td>8</td><td><strong>Policy &amp; governance</strong></td><td>Written policy published; data classes defined; incident process exists</td></tr><tr><td>9</td><td><strong>Hiring alignment</strong></td><td>AI fluency is a documented role requirement; assessed in interviews</td></tr><tr><td>10</td><td><strong>Investment compounding</strong></td><td>Year-over-year increase in workflows; budget allocated for next year</td></tr></tbody></table></div></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Distribution by company size — May 2026</span><h2 class="h2">Where companies cluster</h2><div class="table-wrap"><table class="t"><thead><tr><th>Company size</th><th>Median Index score</th><th>Range (25-75)</th><th>% scoring 50+</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>10-25 people</td><td>38</td><td>22-58</td><td>~35%</td></tr><tr><td>25-50 people</td><td>42</td><td>25-60</td><td>~40%</td></tr><tr><td>50-100 people</td><td>45</td><td>28-65</td><td>~45%</td></tr><tr><td>100-250 people</td><td>48</td><td>30-70</td><td>~50%</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p class="body"><strong>Observation:</strong> Company size correlates weakly with Index score in our sample. The strongest predictor is leadership commitment (dimension 1), not size. Some 25-person companies score 70+; some 200-person companies score below 30.</p></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Distribution by industry — May 2026</span><h2 class="h2">Which verticals lead</h2><div class="table-wrap"><table class="t"><thead><tr><th>Industry</th><th>Median Index score</th><th>% scoring 50+</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>B2B SaaS</td><td>52</td><td>~55%</td></tr><tr><td>Professional services (agencies, consulting)</td><td>48</td><td>~50%</td></tr><tr><td>E-commerce / DTC</td><td>45</td><td>~45%</td></tr><tr><td>Financial services</td><td>38</td><td>~35%</td></tr><tr><td>Manufacturing (mid-market industrial)</td><td>35</td><td>~30%</td></tr><tr><td>Healthcare (private practices)</td><td>32</td><td>~25%</td></tr><tr><td>Nonprofit</td><td>28</td><td>~20%</td></tr><tr><td>Real estate (brokerages)</td><td>28</td><td>~20%</td></tr></tbody></table></div></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Year-over-year movement</span><h2 class="h2">Index trajectory since 2024</h2><div class="table-wrap"><table class="t"><thead><tr><th>Date</th><th>Sample median</th><th>Top quartile</th><th>Bottom quartile</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>May 2024</td><td>18</td><td>38</td><td>6</td></tr><tr><td>Nov 2024</td><td>24</td><td>46</td><td>8</td></tr><tr><td>May 2025</td><td>32</td><td>56</td><td>14</td></tr><tr><td>Nov 2025</td><td>37</td><td>60</td><td>20</td></tr><tr><td><strong>May 2026</strong></td><td><strong>42</strong></td><td><strong>64</strong></td><td><strong>24</strong></td></tr></tbody></table></div><p class="body"><strong>Observation:</strong> The median has roughly doubled over 24 months. The bottom quartile has moved up faster than the top — the floor is rising. The top quartile continues advancing but at a slower rate; pushing from 60 to 80 is harder than 30 to 50.</p></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">How to score your own company</span><h2 class="h2">Self-assessment</h2><p class="body">Score honestly 0-10 on each dimension. Sum for your Index score.</p><ol class="ol"><li><strong>Leadership commitment:</strong> 0 = CEO doesn't use AI; 5 = uses occasionally; 10 = daily, publicly, models for team.</li><li><strong>Named ownership:</strong> 0 = no one owns it; 5 = part-time owner without protected time; 10 = full-time-equivalent owner with mandate.</li><li><strong>Platform consolidation:</strong> 0 = sprawl of personal tools; 5 = enterprise license but inconsistent use; 10 = one platform, deep adoption.</li><li><strong>Production workflows:</strong> 0 = none; 5 = 1-2 in production; 10 = 5+ across functions.</li><li><strong>Documentation:</strong> 0 = nothing documented; 5 = some prompts saved; 10 = workflow docs maintained, prompt library lives.</li><li><strong>Measurement:</strong> 0 = no baselines; 5 = some workflows measured; 10 = systematic measurement + quarterly review.</li><li><strong>Team adoption:</strong> 0 = no one uses; 5 = ~40% weekly active; 10 = 80%+ weekly active in affected functions.</li><li><strong>Policy:</strong> 0 = no policy; 5 = informal rules; 10 = published policy + incident process.</li><li><strong>Hiring alignment:</strong> 0 = not assessed; 5 = mentioned in some role specs; 10 = required and assessed in interviews.</li><li><strong>Investment compounding:</strong> 0 = flat or shrinking; 5 = maintained; 10 = systematic year-over-year growth.</li></ol></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Interpretation</span><h2 class="h2">What your score means</h2><ul class="ul"><li><strong>0-25 (Exploring):</strong> AI usage is individual, not organizational. Big upside available.</li><li><strong>26-50 (Piloting):</strong> Some workflows in production, ownership unclear. Most common state in May 2026.</li><li><strong>51-75 (Operationalizing):</strong> Real adoption with infrastructure. Continued investment compounds.</li><li><strong>76-100 (Compounding):</strong> AI fluency is part of how the company operates. Hard to reach; durable advantage.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Methodology</span><h2 class="h2">How the Index is computed</h2><ul class="ul"><li>Sample: ~60 B2B mid-market companies, \$5M-\$50M ARR, Q4 2024-Q2 2026.</li><li>Each company scored on 10 dimensions during engagement intake, mid-engagement review, or post-engagement follow-up.</li><li>Scoring done by Treetop consultants based on observation; not self-report.</li><li>Year-over-year tracking includes companies scored at multiple points in time.</li><li>Sample skews toward B2B SaaS and professional services; light coverage of pure consumer brands.</li><li>Refresh cadence: quarterly. Last refresh: May 2026.</li></ul><div class="callout"><p><strong>Methodology caveat:</strong> The sample is biased toward companies investing seriously in AI rollout (they hired a consultancy). Treat the absolute numbers as biased upward; treat year-over-year deltas and distributional patterns as more reliable.</p></div></div></section>

